The High Court rooms in Lagos State will not be opened for litigations from July 25 to September 16, 2022. This is because the Chief Judge, Justice Kazeem Alogba, has approved the period as long vacation for Judges in the state. This was contained in a public notice issued yesterday by acting Chief Registrar, Tajudeen Ellias. The statement said Justice Alogba approved the vacation period pursuant to Order 49 Rule 4(D) of the High Court of Lagos Civil Procedure Rules 2019. It added that arrangements have been made to entertain urgent matters during the vacation. Four judges have been assigned to adjudicate on proceedings at the Ikeja Division and the Lagos Division, while two judges were assigned each to Badagry, Epe and Ikorodu Divisions of the High Court during the vacation.   Akeredolu, Sanwo-Olu, others for Attorneys-General’s…     Oyetola to journalists: avoid reports that undermine our…     Tallen, Falana, for women’s conference   At the Ikeja Division, Justice O. A. Taiwo will be sitting from July 25 to August 5; Justice O. A. Okunuga (August 8 to 19); Justice A.O Adeyemi (August 12 to September 5) and Justice Y. R. Pinheiro (September 5 to 16). At the Lagos Division, Justice O. F. Aigbokhaevbo will sit from July 25 to August 5; Justice O. O. Martins (August 8 to 19); Justice O. O. Oshin (August 22 to September 2) and Justice A. M. Ipaye-Nwachukwu (September 5 to 16). In the Badagry Division, Justice M.O. Dawodu will sit from August 8 to 19; Justice B.O. Kalaro (August 22 to September 2); Justice A.O. Idowu will sit at the Epe Division from August 8 to August 19 and Justice I.O. Ojelu from August 22 to September 2. At the Ikorodu Division, Justice O.A. Odusanya will sit from August 8 to 19 and Justice M.I. Oshodi from August 22 to September 2. According to the notice, the 2022/2023 court session begins on September 19, while the new legal year services will hold on September 26.